items.title: Juncus flavidus
items.content_text: Keyed out to flavidus and fits FoV description. Culm dull green, 4mm diameter, 1m tall, pith with spaces. Long, loose cataphyll, straw upper and red-brown lower.

items.title: Juncus remotiflorus
items.content_text: Keyed out & fits FoV description. Pith with airholes rules out most other contenders. Culms blue-green, soft, 2.5mm diameter, ~50-70 striations not strongly raised. Primary bract continuous with culm. 60cm tall in temporary wet area in dry forest.

items.title: Eucalyptus polyanthemos subsp. vestita

items.content_text: Some lovely Blue Box specimens along Coimadai Creek. Red (12223) & Blue Box occur here. Blue is creekside & Red away from creek. Easiest to separate on fruit shape, although Red has greener upper foliage too. Red can be mallee-like here.

items.title: Hydrocotyle sibthorpioides
items.content_text: 2m mat in dried up flow area of upper reaches of creek. Frill of hairs at top of leaf stem (pic 3). Leaves glabrescent/shining above (only long fine hairs on upper surface) and some hairs visible on leaf under-surface. New species for Riddell.

items.title: Ranunculus glabrifolius
items.content_text: Fruit and leaf seem to confirm species. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Hypericum spp.
items.content_text: Possibly H. japonicum. Large patch in dried up flow area of upper reaches of creek. Small flowers compared to gramineum plants in drier areas nearby. Would be a new species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Cassytha glabella f. dispar

items.title: Xanthorrhoea australis
items.content_text: Two plants flowering following a late burn (some time Autumn-Winter, not sure when).

items.title: Plantago debilis
items.content_text: Sepals about 1.5mm long. Flower/fruit is much smaller than for P. varia. This plant found in a damper roadside, reconfirms the species for Riddells Creek as found by I. Lunt in 1984/5. First time I've seen it in Riddells Creek.

items.title: Fletchamia mediolineata
items.content_text: Sitting on a waterside log, then moved into the water. Spotted by Lydia Best. ID by LW - see comments.

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. armeria
items.content_text: This plant about 1.2m tall, very long leaves and large flowers (relative to the other subsp. depicted nearby in observation 11370).

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
items.content_text: Recent burn has revealed numerous plants (we saw 25ish so possibly 100ish overall) spread over a narrow area with limits as detailed by the 3 plants depicted here.

items.title: Heteronympha merope merope, Myrmecia pilosula
items.content_text: Common Browns mating (female above, male below) while Jumping Jack attacks the head of the female.

items.title: Pseudocheirus peregrinus
items.content_text: Ringtail Possums all through this section of Barrm Birrm.

items.title: Myiagra cyanoleuca
items.content_text: I heard this bird move in at my place just over a year ago but this is the first time caught on camera.

items.title: Isometroides angusticaudus
items.content_text: ID confirmed by KW who adds that the species seems to occur in a very tight corner of NW Victoria with single records in close by NSW and SA (see ALA map).

items.title: Scarabaeidae spp.
items.content_text: Burrowing beetle - made heaps of noise when burrowing at night, then the castings at the precise spot the next morning. At Rocket Lake. Large front 'paddles' and long 'toes' look a little like Heteronychus arator.

items.title: Eucalyptus globulus subsp. bicostata
items.content_text: This subspecies is defined by fruit in 3s and fruit sessile (stalkless). Small copse of young trees - not aware of any other populations in Riddells Creek. Possibly be a weed but hard to tell.

items.content_text: Along with previous observation (10253), this shows the limits of the positions where this new species record for Wilsons Prom was seen - about 6-10 plants seen on the side of the track. Plants were open in pouring rain (no sun).

items.title: Thelymitra malvina
items.content_text: New species record for Wilsons Prom. Nearest records are west of Korumburra and Providence Ponds Reserve (east of Sale). Distinctive mauve tufts on column arms. Apparently opens only in mornings. These were open in pouring rain (no sun).

items.content_text: Location approximate - to about 20m.

items.content_text: Two plants within a few cm of each other, possibly joined by rhizome. None others noted but didn't have time to look closely. This fills a bit of a missing link in the species distribution. Again in its drier soil habitat.

items.content_text: Only one plant flowering on long walk. All other plants not flowering. Spindly small tree to 2m is typical in the Riddells Creek forest areas.

items.title: Cracticus nigrogularis
items.content_text: Beautiful singing to wake up to.

items.content_text: Yarrara Flora and Fauna Reserve.

items.content_text: Soggy male. New research has suggested size of a male kangaroo's forearms is a key factor in their ability to find and keep mates.

items.title: Callitris verrucosa
items.content_text: It had just rained which is why the colour of the fruit appears two-tone.

items.title: Iridomyrmex agilis
items.content_text: Carrying away one of its own species.

items.title: Acacia oswaldii
items.content_text: Distinctive spiraling seedpod.

items.title: Ardea pacifica
items.content_text: Ordinary pic but useful as confirmation of the record, a new record for the Neds Corner birds collection. Far away and flew off before I could get close.

items.title: Egretta novaehollandiae

items.content_text: Third pic is  different individual.

items.title: Mustela furo
items.content_text: Spotted while doing a NatureShare presentation to APS Mitchell. Probably an escaped pet (quite tame). Seemed to be hiding/living behind the fridge at Kilmore Library.

items.title: Wallabia bicolor
items.content_text: Jumping on and off fallen tree trunks. Eating grass and nibbling on bracken.

items.content_text: Distinctive dark hairs on buds make them look blackish.

items.content_text: Either var. lanceolatus (more likely) or var. maritimus. Needs phyllary info for full ID.

items.content_text: Victoria's only Thomasia (rare in Vic).

items.content_text: Verging on L. scoparium on some plants (eg. pic1) but leaves broadest at base and tapering to tip as per L. continentale (see especially pic2). Unusual forms of many species in this swamp.

Boronia parviflora
items.content_text: Pale pink and white flowered plants. Large sepals are a key feature.

items.title: Thelionema umbellatum

items.title: Arthropodium strictum s.s.
items.content_text: Curiously flowering with A. sp. 3 (see notes on 9267 for comparison). Yellow base to anthers, drooping flower stems, all nodes have a single flower.
